Perfect 👍 You’ve already got Postgres running as db with user app and db appdb.
There are two easy ways to “see” your data:

🔎 1. Use psql inside the db container
docker compose exec db psql -U app -d appdb -c "\dt"


👉 shows all tables/views.

docker compose exec db psql -U app -d appdb -c "SELECT * FROM person LIMIT 5;"
docker compose exec db psql -U app -d appdb -c "SELECT * FROM ride LIMIT 5;"
docker compose exec db psql -U app -d appdb -c "SELECT * FROM pay_summary LIMIT 5;"


👉 shows first 5 rows from each.

🔎 2. Query through your app container (SQLAlchemy session)

If you’ve set up backend/db.py with a SessionLocal, you can run:

docker compose run --rm app bash -lc '
python - <<PY
from backend.db import SessionLocal
from backend.models import Person, Ride
from sqlalchemy import text

db = SessionLocal()

print("\\nPeople:")
for row in db.query(Person).limit(5):
    print(row.__dict__)

print("\\nRides:")
for row in db.query(Ride).limit(5):
    print(row.__dict__)

print("\\nPay summary view:")
for row in db.execute(text("SELECT * FROM pay_summary LIMIT 5")):
    print(row)
PY
'

🔎 3. Export to CSV

If you want to dump tables to CSV from inside the container:

docker compose exec db psql -U app -d appdb -c "\copy person TO '/var/lib/postgresql/data/person.csv' CSV HEADER"


That puts person.csv inside the db’s data directory.
If you prefer into your project’s data/out/, mount that volume into the db service:
	
db:
  ...
  volumes:
    - pgdata:/var/lib/postgresql/data
    - ./data/out:/data/out


Then:

docker compose exec db psql -U app -d appdb -c "\copy person TO '/data/out/person.csv' CSV HEADER"


Now you’ll see data/out/person.csv on your Mac.

